pr_review_comment_body:
@mwarkentin @ravangen, I was thinking that including the class name might make messages clearer by providing more context, as well as helping to distinguish between errors that don't have a message or that have the same message but a different exception class. This could help with services like Sentry that automatically try to group issues.

But based on looking through a bunch of errors, the cases where including the class name would help are pretty unusual. Usually the message alone without the class name is quite clear, and exceptions will almost always have messages that are unique.

Since it doesn't have a high value, I have removed the class name, which will make the messages more readable.

Actually I already wrote a _get_json method which you can copy (I might add it as part of bug 1163138):

    def _get_json(self, project, endpoint):
        resp = requests.get(self._get_uri(project, endpoint), timeout=self.timeout)
        resp.raise_for_status()
        return resp.json()

